{{Infobox country at games | NOC = KOR | NOCname = [[Korean Olympic Committee]] | oldcode = | year = 2002 | date = | games = Asian Games | location = [[Busan]] | competitors = 769 | sports = 36 | flagbearer = | officials = 238 | gold = 96 | silver = 80 | bronze = 84 | rank = 2 | appearances = auto | seealso = | website = }}
'''[[South Korea]]''' (officially the '''Republic of Korea''') was the host nation of the '''[[2002 Asian Games]]''' held in [[Busan]] from September 29 to October 14, 2002. South Korea was represented by the [[Korean Olympic Committee]], and the South Korean delegation was the largest in this edition of the [[Asian Games]]. The delegation of 1,008 people included 770 competitors&nbsp;– 460 men, 310 women&nbsp;– and 238 officials (217 men and 21 women). [[North Korea at the 2002 Asian Games|North Korea]] competed for the first time in an international sporting event hosted by South Korea. Both nations marched together at the opening ceremony with a [[Korean Unification Flag]] depicting the [[Korean Peninsula]] as [[Korean reunification|United Korea]].
Competitors from the South Korea led the bronze medal count with 84 in the [[2002 Asian Games medal table|general medal table]]. South Korea also won 96 gold medals, 80 silver medals and a total of 260 medals, finishing second on the medal table.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ocasia.org/Game/MWinner.aspx?AMWCode=18&GCode=1 | title=Overall medal standings&nbsp;– Busan 2002 | publisher=ocasia.org. [[Olympic Council of Asia]] | accessdate=January 30, 2012}}</ref>
==Background== South Korea hosted the Asian Games for the second time after the [[1986 Asian Games]] in [[Seoul]]. 2002 Asian Games (officially known as the 14th Asian Games) came out to be politically successful for the host nation as this was the first time in the history that [[North Korea at the 2002 Asian Games|North Korea]] competed in an international sporting event hosted by their southern neighbor.<ref name="economist ">{{cite news | url=http://www.economist.com/node/1371329?story_id=1371329 | title=The Koreas united, for a day | work=[[The Economist]] | date=October 3, 2002 | accessdate=January 30, 2012 | location=[[City of Westminster|Westminster]]}}</ref>
[[National Olympic Committee]] of South Korea, Korean Olympic Committee, selected a delegation consisted of 770 athletes (460 men and 310 women) and 238 officials (217 men and 21 women).<ref name="delegation">{{cite web | url=http://www.busanasiangames.org/Eng/ag/ba_elist_by_nat.asp | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030623062803/http://www.busanasiangames.org/Eng/ag/ba_elist_by_nat.asp | archivedate=June 23, 2003 | title=Participation General&nbsp;– Each National & Regional | publisher=busanasiangames.org. Busan Asian Games Organizing Committee | accessdate=January 30, 2012}}</ref> This was the largest delegation of any nation in the Games, comparing with the second largest delegation of [[Japan at the 2002 Asian Games|Japan]] which included 659 athletes and 329 officials.<ref name="delegation" />
==Medal summary== {{See also|2002 Asian Games medal table}} Korean contingents earned total 260 medals in 38 sports and disciplines. In the national sport [[Taekwondo at the 2006 Asian Games|Taekwondo]], Korean athletes won most medals (twelve gold, three silver and a bronze).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.busanasiangames.org/eng/ag/ba_res_by_nat.asp?NAT_CD=KOR | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030623011911/http://www.busanasiangames.org/eng/ag/ba_res_by_nat.asp?NAT_CD=KOR | archivedate=June 23, 2003 | title=Medal Standing (view by sport)&nbsp;– Korea | publisher=busanasiangames.org. Busan Asian Games Organizing Committee | accessdate=January 30, 2012}}</ref>
